## What happened

In **.NET 11**, Apple's cryptography libraries dropped DSA support, and .NET surfaces this as a runtime exception. `DSA.Create()` (and any DSA signing/verification) now **throws on macOS**. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy DSA signatures, you have two options:

**Option A — Platform guard (minimal change):**
Skip DSA verification on macOS, or gate it so the DSA code path only runs on Windows/Linux:

```csharp
if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    dsa.ImportParameters(legacyKey);
    bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
}
else
{
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
        "DSA signature verification is not supported on macOS with .NET 11+.");
}
```

**Option B — Migrate to ECDSA/RSA (recommended long-term):**
Re-sign the data with a modern algorithm and verify against the new signatures:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
var valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

This requires a one-time re-signing step for all legacy artifacts.

**Which to choose?** If you must keep verifying existing DSA signatures without re-signing, use **Option A** and accept that macOS can't perform the verification. If you can re-sign, **Option B** future-proofs you across all platforms.
